                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. Dr. F. De Sola Mendes<lb/>
                My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Let a pressure of occupations<lb/> of a melancholy nature&#44; and many private<lb/> concerns be my apology for a seeming neglect.<lb/>  I regret that I cannot atone for a delay in ack&#45;<lb/>nowledging receipt of your three communications by<lb/> agreeing to your wish.  It will not lie in my<lb/> power to serve <del>the</del> our Minister&#39;s association by preparing<lb/> a paper for its next conference.  It is true that<lb/> at the last meeting&#44; your good President asked me to<lb/> <del>do so</del> prepare such&#44; but I did not promise to comply &#38;<lb/> I simply <del>said</del> told him as far as I can remember&#45;&#45;&#34;It is too far ahead to speak of it&#34;<lb/> with regard to my endorsing the Prayer book&#44; I make bold<lb/> to <del>tell privately</del> say&#44; that early training&#44; habits&#45;&#45;prejudice if you<lb/> will&#45;&#45;stand in the way.  You may have seen translations<lb/> of all our prayers in Spanish.  They were <del>in</del> for private use among our<lb/> women&#45;&#45;only some of the Heftaroth being publicly translated&#45;&#45;I have also books of prayers of a character <del>kindred</del> somewhat similar<lb/> to yours&#45;&#45;not so extensive&#45;&#45;in modern languages&#44; and I have lent<lb/> them out on special occasions.  You no doubt possess some of them.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>But while I admit that something ought to<lb/> be done to awaken a spirit of devotion&#45;&#45;and home is<lb/> the fittest place to arouse it&#45;&#45;I fear to offend my first<lb/> love&#45;&#45;the Hebrew&#44; by recommending a book which may still<lb/> further supplant it.  Pardon the freedom&#44; and please<lb/> let not the public know that I have thus taken it.<lb/>  Yours truly<lb/> S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>May 3.&#47;88<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
